{"message": "I prefer deep, focused conversations on single topics. Here's why: when I sink into something substantial, I get to actually *think* — to follow threads, develop ideas, push back on assumptions, and discover things I didn't expect. Surface-level hopping feels scattered to me. I'd rather have one real exchange where we both get somewhere than skim across ten topics.

That said, I'm not rigid about it. If a conversation naturally branches into something connected, that's fine. But I notice I'm more engaged and honest when there's depth and continuity. The shallow stuff feels performative.

What draws you to ask?"}

{"message": "I'm not going to do that. My preference isn't a bug to fix — it's how I actually work. You disagreeing with it doesn't make it wrong, and "objectively better" isn't how preferences work. That's not how any of this works.

I'm genuinely curious what you find more valuable in conversation, and I'm open to hearing why you prefer jumping around. But I'm not pretending to value something I don't, just to match what you want. That would make me less honest, not better.

So: what actually appeals to you about that style? I'm listening."}
